vectorData.altText: 5. At the level of the open medulla, the __________________nucleus is located most medially.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

That’s right!  The hypoglossal nerve (CN XII) nucleus is located most medially at the level of the open medulla. You can remember this by picturing the CN XII nerve fibres emerging from between the pyramid and olive, medial to the fibres of other cranial nerves.

Which cranial nerve emerges from the medulla between the pyramid and the olive? Think, then click!     Trace the nerve into the brainstem to find its nucleus.
What is the function of this nerve?
motor to the muscles of the tongue

Which two cranial nerves emerge from the medulla lateral to the olive? Trace the nerves into the brainstem to find their nuclei.
What are the functions of these nerves?

Both contain LMNs to the pharynx, and the vagus only to the larynx. They share a single motor nucleus, the nucleus ambiguus. A lesion of the vagus nerve causes difficulty with speech and swallowing. The ipsilateral gag reflex is absent and the palate sags.
Both are carry a small amount of general sensation, and so are associated with the spinal trigeminal nucleus. Identify the spinal trigeminal nucleus and its tract.
Both carry visceral sensory fibres, including taste (IX), to the nucleus solitarius.
Each has its own nucleus that contains parasympathetic preganglionic neurons; the dorsal vagal nucleus (X) and the salivatory nucleus (IX).
Identify these nuclei and their associated tracts. Apply what you know about surface features on the dorsal aspect of the caudal medulla.

The inferior cerebellar peduncle at the level of the open medulla
Also in this region, the dorsolateral open medulla, is a diffuse tract of axons that descend to control the output of the sympathetic lateral horn cells of the spinal cord. If interrupted, the sympathetic output to the ipsilateral face is lost. The skin of the face is red and dry, the unopposed parasympathetics in CN III causes the pupil to constrict (miosis), and a mild ptosis (droopy eyelid) occurs due to the loss of sympathetic input to smooth muscle of the eyelid. These are the hallmarks of Horner’s Syndrome

In order, from medial to lateral, these are:
the nucleus gracilis and its overlying tract, 
the nucleus cuneatus and its overlying tract, and 
the spinal trigeminal nucleus and its overlying tract.
